dspace-development.title: Updating submission forms to reflect industry standards
How should DataSpace handle the versioning of data sets?

comments.body:
Proposals to address this problem are being tracked in this Google doc:
https://docs.google.com/document/d/13ibT_OhCpgyW66asKcn_cASqQkJ8ArGv8qV6vnq0Q50

### Conclusion

> There remains no industry standard for versioning large datasets. In 2015 the Research Data Alliance interviewed 33 organizations including NASA and Zenodo, and found 33 different workflows. They pursued some kind of standard process for 4 years and, from my reading, were still unable to delineate clear guidelines.
>
> PRDS’s goals are to enact a data versioning workflow more open and rigorous than any of our peers, wanting every version properly cited and quickly downloadable through a GUI, without sacrificing storage efficiency. But Globus and Git, the two pieces of software necessary for efficient data transfer and version storage, have not been combined anywhere.
>
> PRDS’s goals aren’t unique to Princeton, giving DRDS the unique opportunity to build that infrastructure if given significant developer time and if it were made a singular priority. Combining S3 versioning, the Globus CLI and Python SDK, and Git LFS, there may be a path forward to create a user interface that points directly to the version requested, but that would require a significant amount of custom infrastructure, with no promise of success. If successful, however, we’d be solving a problem central to many of our peers.
>
> In the short term, there exists no way to efficiently store versioned items in Globus in a user-friendly way. PRDS will need to determine priorities. Assuming strict adherence to their own standards, either (a) they can store datasets inefficiently, and simply double their datasets for each version, or (b) use git to version their datasets and provide documentation allowing users to checkout earlier versions of the dataset.

comments.body: I think there are still too many results, and that it should mimic the behavior of pulfa 2 where one gets only 4 results regardless of how one enters the name. The other results that are displaying in pulfalight have nothing to do with Frederick Vinton. https://findingaids.princeton.edu/?v1=Vinton%2C+Frederick++&f1=kw&b1=AND&v2=&f2=kw&b2=AND&v3=&f3=kw&year=before&ed=&ld=&rpp=10&start=0 vs. https://findingaids-beta.princeton.edu/?utf8=%E2%9C%93&group=true&search_field=all_fields&q=Vinton%2C+Frederick.
@faithc Even https://findingaids-beta.princeton.edu/catalog/C0344 ? (Fourth result down on Pulfalight)

There's a good chance https://findingaids-beta.princeton.edu/catalog/TC011_c194 is a match too, which wouldn't match if Frederick had to be included. How about I set the minimum must match on staging after it indexes everything and we can see how it looks?

That's "Rand, Vinton" and "Rand, Wakefield" though. 

Guess we could try that, but I still think whatever method is being used on the current site seems appropriate.
The indexing backends are different, so I'm not sure we'll hit precisely the same results coming back, but I can definitely make it stricter so we can see how it goes.

(Sorry for the back and forth, by the way, I've personally always preferred too-many-results with the relevant ones popping up at the top, rather than fewer results where I worry I miss things - too much google I guess. 😅 )
Ha, that's ok. It's good to think through, but I definitely think stricter matching is the way to go for this site. Just wanna loop @ccleeton in too.
This seems good to me. I think we will know if its more of an issue when the staff starts to use it.
